Climate Data Analysis Part 2: Modeling and Predicting Average Global Temperatures¶

This notebook will use the data cleaned and stored in the previous one. The data is loaded from SQL into pandas. It is then modeled with Scikit-Learn's LinearRegression(), which is chosen for its simplicity and effectiveness in modeling this type of data. The X and y variables are set, and scaled with the StandardScaler().

#Create a function to get month from the year+decimal index

def get_month(year):
    base = int(year)
    return int(np.round((year - base) * 12.5))

df_geo['month'] = df_geo.index.to_series().apply(get_month)

Mean absolute error for the stable section of the complete set: 0.14305676367457787

The model seems to struggle with the higher variability of the old temperature numbers. Once the data recording becomes more stable, it fits the data better. Overall, with such a small number of features, and lightning-fast training and predicting, this performance is very satisfactory. The Mean Absolute Error of the model, for the shuffled testing set is around 0.2 degrees Celsius. For the whole dataset, the model's MAE is around the same. However, if we test on only the last 6000 samples, which spans over the 1860-2011 period, the error drops to 0.14 degrees Celsius.

Extrapolating Data for Future Predictions¶

To make predictions of the future, we must create data for it. The creation of the data is actually the most difficult part of the process! I chose to use Scikit-Learn as a helper. For CO2 extrapolations, I create a new training and testing set, and fit a polynomial model that predicts the amount of CO2 from the year, and month as features. The model is trained on the last 2000 findings, as the latest trend is going to be the best source for creating future predictions!

In [21]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
X_co2 = df_geo['month'].reset_index()
y = df_geo['co2'].reset_index(drop=True)

month_dummies = pd.get_dummies(X.month, prefix='month')

poly = PolynomialFeatures(3)
X_poly_co2 = pd.DataFrame(poly.fit_transform(np.array(X_co2.year).reshape(-1, 1)))
X_co2 = pd.merge(X_poly_co2.drop(0, axis=1), month_dummies, left_index=True, right_index=True)
In [22]:
model_extrapolate_co2 = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=False, n_jobs=-1)
model_extrapolate_co2.fit(X_co2[-2000:], y.values[-2000:])
Out[22]:
LinearRegression(copy_X=True, fit_intercept=False, n_jobs=-1, normalize=False)
In [23]:
preds = model_extrapolate_co2.predict(X_co2[-4000:])
actual_co2 = y.values[-4000:]
pd.DataFrame({'preds' : preds, 
              'actual' : actual_co2}, index=df_geo.index[-4000:]).iplot(theme='ggplot',
                                                                   title='CO2 Polynomial fit. Predictions of CO2 levels are made based on year and month',
                                                                   yTitle='CO2 levels',
                                                                    xTitle='Year')

It works!¶

The model learns the end of the CO2 pattern, from month and year perfcetly! This will be used to create our CO2 estimates for the future.

We now need to create a timeline for future predictions. I chose to forecast the years 2012-2025, using NumPy's linspace(). The new features also need to be transformed into polynomials for our CO2-model to create predictions for the future.

In [24]:
POINT_START = 2012
POINT_END = 2025
POINTS_PER_YEAR = 35

future_years = np.linspace(POINT_START, POINT_END, (POINT_END - POINT_START) * POINTS_PER_YEAR)
future_months = []

for year in future_years:
    future_months.append(get_month(year))

future_month_dummies = pd.get_dummies(future_months, prefix='month')

future_poly = pd.DataFrame(poly.fit_transform(np.array(future_years).reshape(-1, 1)))
future_X = pd.merge(future_poly.drop(0, axis=1), future_month_dummies, left_index=True, right_index=True)
In [25]:
preds_future = model_extrapolate_co2.predict(future_X)
pd.DataFrame({'preds' : preds_future}, index=future_years).iplot(theme='ggplot',
                                                                 title='CO2 Forecast for 2012-2025.',
                                                                 yTitle='CO2 levels',
                                                                 xTitle='Year')

Solar extrapolation¶

The solar irradiance follows a predictable pattern, and I have no intelligent way of making assumptions on its future behaviour. Therefore, I chose to simply repeat the pattern at the end of the training data.

In [26]:
y = df_geo['total_solar'].reset_index(drop=True)
future_solar = pd.Series(np.repeat(y[-(POINT_END - POINT_START) * POINTS_PER_YEAR:], 1))
future_solar.index = future_years
future_solar.iplot(theme='ggplot',
                   title='Total Solar Irradiance Used for Forecast',
                   yTitle='Total Solar Irradiance',
                   xTitle='Year')

Volcanic activity¶

As the volcanic activity is very unpredictable and sparsely occurring, I decided to use just a constant value of ones, which will standardize around the mean of the volcanic activity of the historical records.

Now it's time to check the shapes of our new features and add them to a dataframe, scale them with the StandardScaler(), and make predictions!

future_volcanic_constant = np.ones(len(future_volcanic))

Assessing our model's performance:¶

Since we trained the model on data until 2011, and there are recorded temperatures until the beginning of 2019, we can examine the quality of our extrapolation of features and the predictions that our model produced.

Quality of CO2 extrapolation¶

To view CO2 concentration changes, the most recent Mauna Loa Observatory data is used. The comparison is plotted below. The model seems to underestimate the growth rate after 2015. Overall it captures the trend rather nicely.

Our extrapolation follows the actual values almost perfectly until 2015, which is very encouraging for future development. As new data comes in, the model can be updated accordingly. If the high performance of this simple model for 3-4 year in the future is sustainable, this process does not have to be repeated very often.

Quality of temperature forecast:¶

To assess the quality of the model's temperature forecast, I downloaded recent global average temperature recordings published by NASA. As the newer data was reported in temperature anomaly, not absolute celsius values, I had to find out the proper modifier to make the numbers equivalent. I ended up using the mean difference in the temperature values as the modifier, which comes in at 8.923556, and adding it to all anomaly records.

In [35]:
%%capture --no-display --no-stdout
#Capture to suppress an ipython ParserWarning
df_temp_recent = pd.read_csv('../data/NASA_Temp_2018.txt', sep='    ', header=None, skiprows=[0, 1, 2, 3, 4])
df_temp_recent.columns = ['year', 'temp_anomaly', 'temp_smoothed']
df_temp_recent['year'] = df_temp_recent['year'].astype('float64')
In [36]:
diff = 8.923556
df_temp_recent['temp'] = df_temp_recent.temp_anomaly + diff
df_temp_recent.index = df_temp_recent['year']

Assessing the predictions¶

There are many ways to express certainty in a model. The downside of sklearn models is often that there is no robust descriptive information of the model's fit, e.g. confidence intervals. In our case, I will check the mean absolute error of our predictions on the historical dataset to see how much an average forecast was off.

This, admittedly quite basic and crude, way of visualizing the expected errors will help in demonstrating the expected zone of actual temperatures, given our prediction. The MAE of our model on the testing set is 0.205 degrees Celsius. This is the number represented by the error bars in the plot. Even the highly deviant 2016 temperature falls into this interval.

Assumptions and concerns¶

The model assumes that the relationship between all the variables and temperature remains linear. Our future prediction also assumes that the rate of increase for CO2 is similar to the early 21st Century rate. Our extrapolated CO2 numbers appear to increase slower than the actual CO2 levels, which suggests that the extrapolation could be fine-tuned. It also assumes that the level of solar irradiance is identical to the previous cycle, and that there are no high seasons of volcanic activity. The undershooting of the CO2 extrapolation leads to slightly low estimates of temperature as well, since CO2 levels heavily influence our model's predictions.

All in all, for such a simple model, it performs well in that it captures the rising trend and some of the seasonality.
